#compdef panopticon
# ============================================================================
# panopticon - customizable command runner on file
#               change with bubbletea TUI (Go,
#               MPL-2.0)
#
# Author : Chris Bender (cfbender)
# Upstream: https://github.com/cfbender/panopticon
#
# `panopticon` watches a project directory tree for
# file changes + runs declared commands when matching
# paths are modified. The TUI (charmbracelet/
# bubbletea) shows each command's name + status +
# last run output in a panel layout, with keyboard
# shortcuts for manually triggering specific commands
# + reviewing logs.
#
# Each command is declared in a per-project config
# file (panopticon's `init` subcommand scaffolds one)
# with:
#   - name: human-readable label for the TUI panel
#   - command: shell command to execute
#   - watch: glob patterns to watch for changes
#   - run-on-start: whether to fire on initial start
#   - timeout: max execution time before killing
#
# When a watched file changes, panopticon walks the
# command table + fires every command whose `watch`
# globs match the changed path. The `--match` flag
# at startup further filters which commands are
# eligible to run (e.g. `--match='build:*'` to only
# run commands whose names start with "build:").
#
# Use cases:
#   - Continuous test+lint+typecheck loop during
#     development (one panel per check)
#   - Continuous build orchestration for multi-
#     language monorepos
#   - Watch-mode for documentation regeneration
#   - Live-reload for static-site generators
#
# Usage:
#   panopticon [options]
#   panopticon init                  # scaffold config
#
# Subcommands:
#   init                  - scaffold a default
#                            panopticon.yaml config
#                            in the cwd
#
# Flags (Go stdlib flag.* parsing):
#   -r, --run-on-start    - run all commands once at
#                            startup
#       --verbose         - log to pan.log
#   -m, --match <glob>    - filter commands by name
#                            glob (default "*")
#       --theme <name>    - theme preset for the TUI
#                            (default theme if empty)
#   -h, --help            - print help
#   -v                    - print version
#
# Configuration file (panopticon.yaml in cwd):
#   commands:
#     - name: "test"
#       command: "go test ./..."
#       watch:
#         - "**/*.go"
#       run-on-start: true
#       timeout: 60s
#     - name: "lint"
#       command: "golangci-lint run"
#       watch:
#         - "**/*.go"
#
# The gobwas/glob lane is built on `github.com/
# gobwas/glob v0.2.3` (declared verbatim at upstream
# go.mod HEAD as a direct dep, imported as
# `"github.com/gobwas/glob"` then `glob.MustCompile(
# match)` in main.go for the `--match` filter +
# similar internal usage for per-command watch
# patterns), the canonical Go globbing library by
# Sergey Kamardin (gobwas) - github.com/gobwas/glob,
# 1700+ stars.
#
# Kamardin started gobwas/glob in 2017 as a Go-
# native alternative to writing ad-hoc glob matchers
# on top of `filepath.Match` (Go's stdlib glob, which
# has limitations: no `**` recursive descent, no
# `{a,b,c}` alternatives, no character classes
# beyond simple `[abc]`).
#
# gobwas/glob's distinguishing implementation
# strategy: *pre-compile glob patterns into a
# finite automaton* + match the path against the
# pre-compiled DFA. This trades a small upfront
# compilation cost for fast repeated matching - the
# same compiled glob can be matched against
# thousands of paths in O(path length) time per
# match, with no allocations after the initial
# compilation.
#
# The compilation strategy matters for tools like
# panopticon that match many paths against the same
# set of patterns over the lifetime of the program.
#
# gobwas/glob is depended on by many production-
# grade Go infrastructure tools:
#   - MinIO (object storage server's bucket-policy
#     glob matching)
#   - Traefik (HTTP reverse proxy's host + path
#     matching)
#   - Grafana (data-source whitelist + alert
#     filter rules)
#   - Datadog Agent (log-collection tagger globs)
#   - Tyk API gateway (route matching)
#   - panopticon (THIS BINARY)
#   - colly (the Go web crawler)
#
# Sergey Kamardin's broader Go ecosystem footprint:
#   - gobwas/glob (canonical Go glob library)
#   - gobwas/ws (WebSocket library used by Mailgun
#     + Discord's Go backends)
#   - gobwas/httphead (HTTP header parser)
#   - gobwas/pool (sync.Pool wrappers)
#   - The broader gobwas org publishing tightly-
#     scoped focused infrastructure libraries
#
# panopticon uses gobwas/glob in main.go:
#   ```go
#   g := glob.MustCompile(match)
#   model := panopticon.NewModel(cancel, g, theme)
#   ```
# The compiled glob is passed to the TUI model
# where each command-name is checked via `g.Match(
# cmd.Name)` during the configuration load.
# Per-command watch patterns get compiled
# separately via the same MustCompile path in the
# config loader.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 261 :: Globbing libraries (shell-style file
#              pattern matching with `*` / `**` /
#              `[]` / `{}` syntax)
# Round 1482 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 261
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : BurntSushi/globset           [R1481 _dropignore]
#             (RegexSet-backed batch
#              matching)
#   Go      : gobwas/glob                  [R1482 THIS FILE]
#             (DFA pre-compilation)
#   TS/Node : isaacs/node-glob             [R1483 closing]
#             (callback-style walker)
#
# gobwas/glob is structurally interesting in this
# axis because of its *pre-compile-once-match-many*
# implementation strategy. The three lanes form a
# clean spectrum of glob-implementation philosophies:
#
#   - Rust (globset): RegexSet-backed batch matching;
#     compiles ALL patterns into a single DFA;
#     matches in O(text length) regardless of pattern
#     count
#   - Go (gobwas/glob): per-pattern DFA pre-
#     compilation; matches each pattern individually
#     but at DFA speed; trades per-pattern
#     compilation for fast repeated matching
#   - Node (node-glob): runtime glob expansion +
#     filesystem walk; older callback-style API;
#     pattern is interpreted rather than compiled
#
# Each lane reflects the host ecosystem's preferred
# matching strategy:
#   - Rust prefers batch DFAs (globset is part of
#     ripgrep's gitignore engine - matching hundreds
#     of patterns per file)
#   - Go prefers per-pattern DFAs (gobwas/glob is
#     used in MinIO/Traefik/Grafana where matching
#     happens at request time)
#   - Node prefers runtime interpretation (node-glob
#     is used at file-walking startup in build tools)
#
# Cross-language interop at the pattern-grammar
# level - the same glob pattern matches the same
# files across all three lanes, modulo edge cases
# around extended globbing features:
#   - `**` recursive descent: all three support
#   - `{a,b,c}` brace alternatives: globset + node-
#     glob support; gobwas/glob supports
#   - `[abc]` character classes: all three support
#   - `[!abc]` negation: all three support
#   - extglob `?(...)` / `*(...)` / `+(...)` /
#     `@(...)` / `!(...)`: node-glob only
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes (so far):
#   - dropignore (Rust, globset): Dropbox sync-ignore
#     bulk applier using globset for pattern
#     matching
#   - panopticon (Go, gobwas/glob): file-watch
#     command runner using gobwas/glob for command
#     filter + watch-pattern compilation
# ============================================================================

_panopticon() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args
    local curcontext="$curcontext" ret=1

    _arguments -C \
        '(-r --run-on-start)'{-r,--run-on-start}'[run all commands once at startup]' \
        '--verbose[log output to pan.log]' \
        '(-m --match)'{-m,--match}'[filter commands by name glob (default *)]:pattern:' \
        '--theme[theme preset for TUI]:theme:' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)-v[print version]' \
        '1: :_panopticon_cmds' \
    && ret=0

    return ret
}

_panopticon_cmds() {
    local -a cmds
    cmds=(
        'init:scaffold a default panopticon config in cwd'
    )
    _describe -t commands 'panopticon command' cmds
}

_panopticon "$@"
